,"id":"106371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent pain in his right proximal tibia. The pain is worse at night and after physical activity. He recalls minor trauma to the leg while playing football six months ago. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild tenderness over the proximal tibia without overlying erythema or swelling. He has a full range of motion at the knee joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a C-reactive protein of 15 mg/L (0-5) and white cell count of 8.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0). Plain radiograph shows a 2.5 cm well-circumscribed lucent lesion with surrounding sclerosis in the proximal tibial metaphysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteoid osteoma","Brodie\u0027s abscess","Osteosarcoma","Ewing sarcoma","Stress fracture"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and radiological findings are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EBrodie\u0027s abscess\u003C/strong\u003E, a form of subacute osteomyelitis. Key features include indolent onset of pain worse at night, minimal systemic symptoms, mildly elevated inflammatory markers, and the characteristic radiological appearance of a well-circumscribed lytic lesion with surrounding sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoid osteoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with night pain that responds dramatically to aspirin or NSAIDs. The radiological appearance would show a small radiolucent nidus (usually \u0026lt;1 cm) with surrounding dense sclerosis, rather than the larger lytic lesion seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows more aggressive radiological features including periosteal reaction, cortical destruction, and a moth-eaten appearance. The lesion would not be well-circumscribed, and patients often have more significant pain and systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEwing sarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more aggressive features including significant pain, systemic symptoms, and an onion-skin periosteal reaction on imaging. The radiological appearance would be more destructive and less well-defined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would typically show a linear lucency on radiograph without the well-circumscribed appearance seen here. The history would usually include recent increase in activity or training, and pain would be more consistently related to weight-bearing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBrodie\u0027s abscess is most commonly caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and requires both surgical debridement and prolonged antibiotic therapy for appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Brodie\u0027s abscess is a subacute osteomyelitis characterised by a well-circumscribed intraosseous abscess with surrounding sclerosis.","The most common causative organism is Staphylococcus aureus.","Management typically involves surgical debridement followed by prolonged antibiotic therapy."],"references":["Gaillard F, Verikios N, Vadera S, et al. Brodie abscess. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 19 Jun 2025). Available from: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88834"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88834"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-19T10:23:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T10:24:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8014"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descript